Prediction of Sleep Hour on Week days

Introduction:

Predicting the hours of sleep a person is taking on weekdays is depends on multiple factors like their mental health, quality of sleep, their sleep hours on weekends or the number of hour daily a person should sleep so they will not feel sleepy. However, there are other factors as well which might affect their sleeping hours. First of all to predict sleeping hours it has been shown by the researchers that Sleep depends on sleep quality and sleep quantity (Williams, J. and Cook, D. 2018). They explained sleep quantity as the amount of sleep needed by individual to make them feel at rest for the day. Previously, researches has been done to predict sleep pattern with the help of quality of sleep people getting in different environment (Merilahti, J., Saarinen, A., Parkka, J., Antila, K., Mattila, E. and Korhonen, I.,2007). Researches trying to get the sleep pattern by analyzing the study conducted between two groups of people. The study conducted for three months, inside and outside of their home. By the analysis of quality of sleep researchers they are trying to predict the sleep pattern. This has been done to test the accuracy of sleep pattern estimation by a device. Moreover, recent researches has been done which shows that anxiety affect the sleep of individuals (Goldstein-Piekarski, A., Greer, S., Saletin, J., Harvey, A., Williams, L. and Walker, M. 2018) although this research was specific to gender but it shows that anxiety play role in sleeping order of individuals. This study based on data collected by Questionnaire for sleep with (N= 271). Based on above mentioned researches the prediction of sleeping pattern in week night depends on following factors:-

1.  Quality of sleep which is categorical variable where range varies from 1 to 4 and defined as 1=very poor, poor ; 2=fair; 3=good;4=very good, excellent.
2.  Average hours of sleep needed not feel sleepy which is continuous data and values provided by individuals (n= 271).
3.  Anxiety score with range from 0-21. This can be considered as continuous as no category defined for each value of range.
4.  Hours of sleep on average each weekend.

The Prediction of average hour of sleep in weekdays is done by using Multiple Linear Regression by creating multiple Models based on below hypothesis

Model 1:

H0: There is no significant prediction of hours of sleep in weekday by hours needed to sleep for not to feel sleepy and anxiety score. HA: There is no significant prediction of hours of sleep in weekday by hours needed to sleep for not to feel sleepy and anxiety score.

Model 2:

H0: There is no significant prediction of hours of sleep in weekday by hours needed to sleep for not to feel sleepy, anxiety score and Quality of Sleep. HA: There is no significant prediction of hours of sleep in weekday by hours needed to sleep for not to feel sleepy, anxiety score and Quality of Sleep.

Model 3:

H0: There is no significant prediction of hours of sleep in weekday by hours needed to sleep for not to feel sleepy, anxiety score, Quality of Sleep and average hour of sleep on weekends. HA: There is no significant prediction of hours of sleep in weekday by hours needed to sleep for not to feel sleepy, anxiety score , Quality of Sleep and average hour of sleep on weekends.

Methodology

The Questionnaire for sleep contains 55 details which have been filled by 271 people. However for prediction of sleep pattern all the details provided is not useful. There are 5 variable of interests used to build the regression model. The variable used for the study contains some missing values which cannot be used for the study.

The data set contains 271 records with few missing values after removing the missing the relevant number of record is 258. This study deals with only 258 relevant records. The variables of interests used for the study are as following:

  1. hourwnit : Prediction of Hours of sleep in weekdays(DEPENDENT VARIABLE)
  2. anxiety : Anxiety Score (INDEPENDENT VARIABLE)
  3. qualsleeprec: Quality of sleep (INDEPENDENT VARIABLE)
  4. hourneed : Hours needed to sleep for not to feel sleepy(INDEPENDENT VARIABLE)
  5. hourwend: Hours of sleep on Weekends(INDEPENDENT VARIABLE)

The Prediction of Dependent Variable is done on the basis of 4 Independent variables mentioned above. There are Three models created with the help of independent variables for the prediction of sleep hours. The Descriptive Statistics of the variables is explained in the next section.

Correlation Between the variables for Multiple Linear Regression:

For multiple linear regressions it is necessary to find correlation between the entire variable to see the changes happen in one variable and its effect on model. So before creating Regression model need to find out correlation between all the independent and dependent variables.

1. Correlation between Dependent and Independent variables:

1.1 Correlation between hourwnit and anxiety

As dependent variable hourwnit and Independent variable anxiety both are continuous therefore pearson correlation is calculated. A Pearsons r data analysis revealed moderate negative correlation. Where r= -0.19, and p < 0.05 which is lower than conventional 5% therefore correlation coefficient is statically significant.

cor.test(sleep_data$hourwnit, sleep_data$anxiety)
## 
##  Pearson's product-moment correlation
## 
## data:  sleep_data$hourwnit and sleep_data$anxiety
## t = -3.1493, df = 256, p-value = 0.001831
## alternative hypothesis: true correlation is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -0.30798418 -0.07271284
## sample estimates:
##       cor 
## -0.193123
#pearson correlation between hourwnit and anxiety

1.2 Correlation between hourwnit and qualsleeprec

As dependent variable hourwnit and Independent variable qualsleeprec test tested categories of Bartletts as quality of sleep is categorical data. Bartletts test represent quality of variance for hour of sleep on weeknights and four categories of quality of sleep (K2 = 7.54, p = 0.05). A one way between the categories is conducted for the analysis of variance to explore the hour of sleep in week night and quality of sleep in different categories. The participant for this test divided into four groups (1 = very poor, poor; 2 = fair; 3 = good; 4 = very good, excellent). There was statically difference level in hour of sleep in week night for the categories of quality of sleep (F = 9.41, p < .05). The effect size calculated by using eta squared was .1. Post-hoc comparisons done by using Tukey HSD test shows that the mean score for Group 1 (M = 1.02, P < .001). Difference between group 2 and 1 is 0.31 that means people having fair sleep is .31 more than the people having poor quality of sleep. Similarly 3 -1 and 4-1 is 0.68 and 1.02 respectively. For group 2-3 and 2-4 have difference of .37 and .71 respectively. Adding to this difference for group 4-3 is .34 that means people having good sleep are .34 more than the people having excellent sleep.

Results

For Multiple Linear Regression, the hour of sleep hourwnit is a response variable and other four variables are the predictor variables. Multiple Linear regressions is about many to one relationship between respondent and predictor variable. The equation for multiple linear regressions is shown below:

y = b0 + b1x1 + b2x2 + .. + bnxn + ei

Here, Y is the response variable which is hourwnit, b0 is the intercept which will be calculated by creating 3 models. B1, B2 , B3 and B4 are the regression coefficient and ei is the error coefficient. Multiple regression analysis is done by creating three models and adding predictor variable one by one.

Model1(Baselie Model)

My baseline model includes respondent variable as hourwnit and predictor variable as hourneed and anxiety. If we compare this with the equation of multiple linear regressions than equation will look like

Y ("hourwnit") = B0 + B1("hourneed")+B2("anxiety")

The correlation between these three variables is already discussed in previous section so now after creating a Baseline Regression model we get coefficients. The prediction of sleep hour in weeknight will be done with the help of data which shows hour needed to sleep for not to feel sleepy next day and anxiety score. After creating the model we will get coefficients and after fitting the coefficients in the equation, it will look like:

Y ("hourwnit") = 4.00075   +  0.43912 ("hourneed") -0.07003  ("anxiety")

To get some more statical result we will analyze summary of regression model 1. The regression model created by Lm function where n is the number of explanatory variable used for the Multiple Linear Regression model.

Lm(response ~ explanatory_1 + explanatory_2 +..+ explanatory_n)

Here most important result is P value which is the probability value. This will indicate that statical significance of the variable is contributing to the model. In this model both the variables hourneed and anxiety are contributing statically significantly to the model. A significant equation was calculated to predict hourwnit based on hourneed" and anxiety. A significant regression equation was found (F(255) = 42.34, p < .001) with R2 of 0.2434. Participants predicted hourneed is equal to 4.00 +0.44 (hourneed) -0.07 (anxiety) where anxiety count in number from 0-17 and hourneed is coded or measured in hour.

regression1 <- lm(hourwnit~hourneed + anxiety, sleep_data)
regression1 #view basic regression model

There are few more analysis for Baseline Model which are explained in below points:

  1. Cooks distance consider the cases on the model, as per (Field (2013)) if cooks distance is >1 then that outlier is point of concern. In this regression model we are getting one point >1 at 157 which need to be analyzed.The other two outliers are at 75 and 246 which is not expected to have as significant impact.

  2. Leverage values lies at 0 indicate that case has no influence and 1 shows that 1 has complete prediction over the influence. Here the outliers far from the leverage line might cause point of concern.

3.VIF values(hourneed, VIF= 1.00; anxiety, VIF= 1.00) and were within acceptable levels (VIF<2.5)(Field (2013)). This has been measured to understand collinearity.

4.The density plot shows the distribution of standardized residuals and shows the distributed error.

#Plot Cooks distance
cook <- 4/((nrow(sleep_data)- length(regression1$coefficients)-1))
plot(regression1, which = 4, cook.levels = cook)

We can illustrate the findings using the median values for hourneed and anxiety.

        Y ("hourwnit") = 4.00075   +  0.43912 (7.0)  -0.07003 (6)
                         = 4 + 3.07384 - 0.48
                         =6.59459

Based on the above prediction, If a persons anxiety level is 6 and Hours needed to sleep for not to feel sleepy next day is 7 hours then we can predict that persons average sleep on weeknight is 6.59 hour.

Model 1

In this model will use result of Baseline model and add one more Independent variable qualsleeprec. This model includes respondent variable as hourwnit and predictor variable as hourneed, anxiety and qualsleeprec. If we compare this with the equation of multiple linear regressions than equation will look like

  Y ("hourwnit") = B0 + B1("hourneed")+B2("anxiety") +B3 ("qualsleeprec")

The correlation between these three variables is already discussed in previous section so now after creating a Regression model we get coefficients. The prediction of sleep hour in weeknight will be done with the help of data which shows hour needed to sleep for not to feel sleepy next day and anxiety score. After creating the model we will get coefficients and after fitting the coefficients in the equation, it will look like:

  Y ("hourwnit") =   2.83396  +  0.44883 ("hourneed") -0.03931 ("anxiety") + 0.32956("qualsleeprec")

In this model both the variables hourneed and qualsleeprec are contributing statically significantly to the model but because of addition of new variable the significance of anxiety is reduced. However, there is one asterisk present at the result there for its still little significant to be considered. A significant equation was calculated to predict hourwnit based on hourneed,qualsleeprec" ,anxiety. A significant regression equation was found (F(254) = 41.68, p < .001) with R2 of 0.322. Participants predicted hourneed is equal to 2.83+0.45(hourneed) -0.03 (anxiety) + 0.33 (qualsleeprec).

Illustration of Model1 by Example

  1. For Quality of sleep = 1

    Y ("hourwnit") = 2.83396 + 0.44883 (7.0) - 0.03931(6) + 0.32956(1)
                   = 2.83396 +3.14181-0.23586+0.32956
                   = 6.06947

  2. For Quality of sleep = 2

    Y ("hourwnit") = 2.83396 + 0.44883 (7.0) - 0.03931(6) + 0.32956(2)
                 = 2.83396 +3.14181-0.23586+0.65912
                 = 6.39907

3.For Quality of sleep = 3

    Y ("hourwnit") = 2.83396 + 0.44883 (7.0) - 0.03931(6) + 0.32956(3)
                       = 2.83396 +3.14181-0.23586+0.98868
                       = 6.72863

4.For Quality of sleep = 4

    Y ("hourwnit") = 2.83396 + 0.44883 (7.0) - 0.03931(6) + 0.32956(2)
                       = 2.83396 +3.14181-0.23586+1.31824
                       = 7.05819

Based on the above prediction, If a persons anxiety level is 6 and Hours needed to sleep for not to feel sleepy next day is 7 hours then we can predict that persons average sleep on weeknight by cateorizing it by quality of sleep. For example persons quality of sleep is 1 i.e very poor than their pridiction for hour of sleep is 6.06947 hour. similary for quality of sleep as fair the pridiction of sleep in weeknight will be 6.39907 hour, for good and Excellent quality of sleep the prediction is 6.72863 hour and 7.5819 hour respectively.

Model 2

In second model will use result of first model and add one more Independent variable hourwend. After adding this variable the significance of anxity become negligible therefore removed anxiety from the model. This model includes respondent variable as hourwnit and predictor variable as hourneed, hourwend and qualsleeprec. If we compare this with the equation of multiple linear regressions than equation will look like

  Y ("hourwnit") = B0 + B1("hourneed")+B3 ("qualsleeprec")+B4("hourwend")

The correlation between these three variables is already discussed in previous section so now after creating a Regression model we get coefficients. The prediction of sleep hour in weeknight will be done with the help of data which shows hour needed to sleep for not to feel sleepy next day and average hour of sleep on weekends. After creating the model we will get coefficients and after fitting the coefficients in the equation, it will look like:

  Y ("hourwnit") =   1.8877 + 0.2308 ("hourneed") +0.2307 ("qualsleeprec") +0.3411 ("hourwend")

In this model both the variables hourneed,qualsleeprec and hourwend are contributing statically significantly to the model. A significant equation was calculated to predict hourwnit based on hourneed,qualsleeprec" ," hourwend. A significant regression equation was found (F(254) = 65.01, p < .001) with R2 of 0.4276. Participants predictedhourneed" is equal to 1.8877 +0.23(hourneed) +0.23 (qualsleeprec) + 0.34(hourwend).

Conclusion

Significance level of the entire model is p < .001. Except anxiety all the variables used for the model are significant and had p < 0.001. The value of R square is increasing by adding variable in each model. The baseline model has R Square = 0.2434 that means variance of sleep hour prediction is 24.34%. After adding one more variable in Model 1 the value of R Square = 0.322 which is increased therefore variance on sleep hour prediction changed to 32.22%. The main concern about these two models is outliers in Cooks distance which have one outlier having cooks distance > 1which was point of concern. The last model i.e Model 2 which has independent variable as hourwed, hourneed and qualsleeprec is the best fit for the linear regression. First of all variance for this model is 43.43% and cooks distance of outliers is < 1 which does not make significant impact on Regression model. Hence, the aim of analysis is to predict hour of sleep in weeknight with the help of three different independent variable. With the variance significance of 43.43 % we will able to predict the sleep hour with confidence level of 43%.
